stix:STIX_Header.stix:Title: Analysis of 5 ZBot Files
stix:STIX_Header.stix:Description:
On 24 July 2013, 5 ZBot files were submitted for analysis. The files call out to 20 different command and control domains.
This document incorporates data originally released as US-CERT MIFR-300158.

stix:Indicator.indicator:Description:
This file is a piece of malware that is custom packed to hinder static analysis. Upon execution, the malware made modifications to the file system. It injects itself into "explorer.exe". It writes files to disk and then deletes files. The following were deleted: %USERPROFILE%\Local Settings\History %USERPROFILE%\Local Settings\Temp\[random_numbers].bat
(Note: The malware's code was executed in a sandbox environment where not all of the applications are installed)
String data located in the executable's .fdata SECTION indicates that the malware is capable of stealing stored account information and credentials used in installed applications such as File Transfer Protocol (FTP), email, and Internet browsers. It gathers directory lists, passwords, port numbers, server names, user names, and browser certificates by retrieving addresses of Windows APIs. It checks if WOW64 is running, obtains volume GUID path, generates a CLSID using the format string "%08X-%04X-%04X-%02X%02X-%02X%02X%02X%02X%02X%02X" and finally collects operating system (OS) and other relevant information.
The strings have a list of passswords used to brute force user accounts. The passwords are: diamond, maggie, maverick, online, spirit, george, friends, dallas, adidas, 1q2w3e, orange, testtest, asshole, apple, biteme, 666666, william, mickey, asdfgh, wisdom, batman, The malware has networking functionality. It implements networking DLLs, "Wsock32.dll" and "Ws2_32.dll". To implement higher level protocols such as FTP and HTTP, it utilizes "Wininet.dll". The malware strings also included a Facebook URL.
Further analysis is needed to determine functionality and the purpose for the use of the website. The malware made attempts to connect to remote websites via port 80 to download files. The remote sites and requested files are: *http://aquasarnami.com/BiZ.exe *http://bremertondisciples.com/p6AERteJ.exe *http://proactionpt.com/7dPmE3P.exe *http://ruffledpaper.com/N7SvZ.exe
Once the malware gathers information, it communicates with a remote site and sends the information via HTTP POST. The remote sites are: *http://webmail.alsultantravel.com:8080/forum/viewtopic.php *http://alsultantravel.com:8080/forum/viewtopic.php *http://webmail.alsultantravel.info:8080/forum/viewtopic.php *http://198.57.130.35:8080/forum/viewtopic.php
A process, "cmd.exe", is created to execute the batch file,"[random numbers].bat". This batch file is created in the %USERPROFILE%\Local Settings\Temp directory. The purpose of the batch file is to delete the original loader file after execution. The [random_numbers].bat syntax is: 
		

	 :ktk 


 del 	 %1 
	if 		 exist 	 %1 	 goto 	 ktk
 del 	 %0

This file, like, "Translink Critical Update.exe", "ATO_TAX_07242013.exe", "Invoice_18072013.exe" and "Package_07232013.exe", makes changes to the file system. The changes are: *Injects itself to "explorer.exe" process: created %WINDIR%\explorer.exe -->%USERPROFILE%\~\DOCS.exe *Writes files to disk and then deletes the files %USERPROFILE%\Local Settings\History %USERPROFILE%\Local Settings\Temp\[random_numbers].bat *Creates a batch file in the %TEMP% directory then deletes the batch file: %USERPROFILE%\Local Settings\Temp\[random_numbers].bat *Creates a process in memory, "cmd.exe", to execute the batch file that deletes the loader file. process: created %USERPROFILE%\~\DOCS.exe --> %WINDIR%\System32\cmd.exe file: delete %WINDIR%\System32\cmd.exe --> %USERPROFILE%\~\DOCS.exe *Uses a password list to brute force the accounts on the victim machine. *Implements similar Windows APIs *A Facebook URL is embedded in the code located in the executable's .fdata SECTION.
The malware made attempts to connect to remote websites via port 80 to download files. The remote sites and requested files are: *http://www.giftedintuitive.com/kQYjoPqY.exe *http://ftp.jason-tooling.com/nhdx.exe *http://198.61.134.93/MM75.exe *http://paulalfrey.com/guBwFA.exe
Connection to additional remote sites via 8080 were also attempted. The remote sites are: *http://webmail.alsultantravel.com:8080/ponyb/gate.php *http://alsultantravel.com:8080/ponyb/gate.php *http://webmail.alsultantravel.info:8080/ponyb/gate.php *http://198.57.130.35:8080/ponyb/gate.php

This file is malware that makes attempts to connect to remote websites via port 80 to download files. The URLs of the remote files that are requested are: *http://aasportsacademy.com/FPzbn.exe *http://abbeyevents.co.uk/fNF1.exe *http://salsaconfuego.com/RCY.exe *http://whiteheadst.com/JrN9Jv.exe
Connection to additional remote sites via 8080 were also attempted, however, there are no HTTP POST messages sent. The remote sites are: *http://prospexleads.com:8080/ponyb/gate.php *http://phonebillssuck:8080/ponyb/gate.php *http://myimpactblog.com:8080/ponyb/gate.php *http://yourprospexblog.com:8080/ponyb/gate.php
A Facebook website was embedded in the code. The relevant malware strings including the password list are located in the executable's .clx SECTION and have similar functionality with the other files previously analyzed in this report.
